I thought that was
an actual real place.

00:11:29.040 --> 00:11:29.980
AUDIENCE: It's a real place.

00:11:29.980 --> 00:11:30.938
ALAN SEALES: It's real?

00:11:30.938 --> 00:11:31.438
OK.

00:11:31.438 --> 00:11:33.271
JESSICA BIEL: You look
at me like I'm crazy.

00:11:33.271 --> 00:11:35.130
ALAN SEALES: I just,
I never heard of it.

00:11:35.130 --> 00:11:37.213
So I look at it like I've
never heard of the name.

00:11:37.213 --> 00:11:38.860
JESSICA BIEL: It's
supposed to be

00:11:38.860 --> 00:11:44.319
a place like New Paltz,
little Upstate, smallish--

00:11:44.319 --> 00:11:46.860
I've never actually spent much
time in that particular place,

00:11:46.860 --> 00:11:47.977
so I don't know how small.

00:11:47.977 --> 00:11:49.560
I don't want to talk
out of turn here,

00:11:49.560 --> 00:11:54.160
but kind of like every
place kind of a place,

00:11:54.160 --> 00:11:55.290
you know I mean right?

00:11:55.290 --> 00:11:58.204
Like could find this sort
of town across the country.

00:11:58.204 --> 00:12:00.370
ALAN SEALES: It's interesting
because every place is

00:12:00.370 --> 00:12:05.670
kind of a place, but I feel like
there are specific characters,

00:12:05.670 --> 00:12:08.270
types of people that we see
in here that exist in all

00:12:08.270 --> 00:12:11.740
of these every places, like
the crazy religious family

00:12:11.740 --> 00:12:18.380
and then your small town
shop owners and what not.

00:12:18.380 --> 00:12:21.670
Was it a conscious
decision to kind of set

00:12:21.670 --> 00:12:24.580
the story in a place like
this, to enhance the characters

00:12:24.580 --> 00:12:28.740
or enhance the story or does
one kind of beget the other?

00:12:28.740 --> 00:12:30.630
JESSICA BIEL: That's
a good question.

00:12:30.630 --> 00:12:36.770
I mean, since this is a
German writer originally,

00:12:36.770 --> 00:12:39.760
I know it was set in
Germany somewhere.

00:12:39.760 --> 00:12:45.610
So I think we were trying to
find a place that would serve

00:12:45.610 --> 00:12:52.685
as the right town in the
States for, I don't know,

00:12:52.685 --> 00:12:56.210
kind of like a place that could
have a character of its own

00:12:56.210 --> 00:12:56.860
in a sense.

00:12:56.860 --> 00:13:00.210
I feel like Upstate kind
of has that feeling of,

00:13:00.210 --> 00:13:03.320
I don't know, there could be
a lot of bubbling, simmering

00:13:03.320 --> 00:13:05.310
things going on
underneath, which

00:13:05.310 --> 00:13:10.200
is sort of what we're talking
about in the show a little bit.

00:13:10.200 --> 00:13:13.260
Kind of like from the outside
things are looking one way

00:13:13.260 --> 00:13:16.180
and then when you
look a little deeper,

00:13:16.180 --> 00:13:18.800
you're seeing something else.

00:13:18.800 --> 00:13:20.965
I'm not trying to
like bag on Upstate,

00:13:20.965 --> 00:13:22.840
like there's some weird
stuff going on there,

00:13:22.840 --> 00:13:24.007
but that's true everywhere--

00:13:24.007 --> 00:13:25.381
ALAN SEALES: Oh
we know there is.

00:13:25.381 --> 00:13:27.540
JESSICA BIEL: --this idea
of presenting ourselves

00:13:27.540 --> 00:13:29.390
in a certain way.

00:13:29.390 --> 00:13:32.807
And maybe that's not
necessarily 100% true.

00:13:32.807 --> 00:13:34.390
ALAN SEALES: I totally
agree with you.

00:13:34.390 --> 00:13:37.000
I grew up in a small
town in North Carolina.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:40.825
So same mountain chain, same
culture, just different areas.

00:13:40.825 --> 00:13:41.950
JESSICA BIEL: There you go.

00:13:41.950 --> 00:13:44.180
ALAN SEALES: But yeah, I
totally agree with that.

00:13:44.180 --> 00:13:46.440
So as executive
producer, did you

00:13:46.440 --> 00:13:48.220
help with any of the
casting of the show?

00:13:48.220 --> 00:13:48.970
Did you have any--

00:13:48.970 --> 00:13:50.610
JESSICA BIEL: Yes, all of it.

00:13:50.610 --> 00:13:54.360
We have been-- it's actually
been an amazing experience.

00:13:54.360 --> 00:13:58.880
And because I am usually
on the other side of it--

00:13:58.880 --> 00:14:01.730
I'm the one putting
myself on tape

00:14:01.730 --> 00:14:03.870
or going in for the
audition and having

00:14:03.870 --> 00:14:06.110
to send these tapes that
you make at home that you're

00:14:06.110 --> 00:14:08.110
so embarrassed about,
like oh, this is horrible.

00:14:08.110 --> 00:14:09.504
The lighting's bad.

00:14:09.504 --> 00:14:11.170
You're by yourself
reading with somebody

00:14:11.170 --> 00:14:12.900
who can't read
lines because it's

00:14:12.900 --> 00:14:16.100
like your mom and the
whole thing's bad.

00:14:16.100 --> 00:14:21.750
I have such a love and
respect for the people

00:14:21.750 --> 00:14:24.716
that have auditioned
for the show because

00:14:24.716 --> 00:14:25.840
of being on the other side.

00:14:25.840 --> 00:14:26.860
It's just so intense.

00:14:26.860 --> 00:14:28.276
I know what they're
going through.

00:14:28.276 --> 00:14:29.510
I know how hard it is.

00:14:29.510 --> 00:14:32.310
And that process
has been super cool.

00:14:32.310 --> 00:14:37.320
I just have a different
take on a reading,

00:14:37.320 --> 00:14:40.170
on the creative
performance part of it

00:14:40.170 --> 00:14:45.070
than, say, some of my other
producers or even our creator

00:14:45.070 --> 00:14:47.110
or our director at the time.

00:14:47.110 --> 00:14:50.040
So it's been amazing
and I love being

00:14:50.040 --> 00:14:53.660
part of that, that part of it.

00:14:53.660 --> 00:14:55.640
ALAN SEALES: Yeah, I
guess now that you've

00:14:55.640 --> 00:14:57.230
seen what it's on
the other side,

00:14:57.230 --> 00:14:59.840
has that changed how you're
approaching new roles?

00:14:59.840 --> 00:15:02.310
Are you even entertaining
new roles yet?

00:15:02.310 --> 00:15:05.179
Are you still working
on finishing this one?

00:15:05.179 --> 00:15:06.970
JESSICA BIEL: I've read
a couple of things,

00:15:06.970 --> 00:15:09.260
but now that we're sort
of in the last stretch

00:15:09.260 --> 00:15:14.460
of the filming, it's
like a cluster some days.

00:15:14.460 --> 00:15:16.940
It's just everything's kind
of piling on top of itself.

00:15:16.940 --> 00:15:19.110
So I haven't really looked
at anything seriously,

00:15:19.110 --> 00:15:20.610
or there hasn't
really been anything

00:15:20.610 --> 00:15:25.380
that I'm really, really excited
about, so I've been focused.

00:15:25.380 --> 00:15:27.410
ALAN SEALES: No comedies?

00:15:27.410 --> 00:15:29.450
JESSICA BIEL: No.

00:15:29.450 --> 00:15:32.290
Not on purpose though.

00:15:32.290 --> 00:15:34.960
I think it's changed
my perspective.

00:15:34.960 --> 00:15:36.060
It just made me mad.

00:15:36.060 --> 00:15:38.352
I'm like, I don't want
to do another audition

00:15:38.352 --> 00:15:40.310
because they're going to
do what I'm doing when

00:15:40.310 --> 00:15:41.601
I'm watching the audition tape.

00:15:41.601 --> 00:15:45.350
It's like, oh, this
person is so good, but--

00:15:45.350 --> 00:15:47.630
because when you feel like
no buts, just hire me.

00:15:47.630 --> 00:15:48.700
I'm great.

00:15:48.700 --> 00:15:49.510
Trust me.

00:15:49.510 --> 00:15:52.634
I can be great for you.

00:15:52.634 --> 00:15:53.300
ALAN SEALES: OK.

