If any of you have questions
for Jessica, line up

00:16:01.960 --> 00:16:03.660
and we can get to those.

00:16:03.660 --> 00:16:04.600
You are a mom now.

00:16:04.600 --> 00:16:05.270
Congratulations.

00:16:05.270 --> 00:16:06.145
JESSICA BIEL: Thanks.

00:16:06.145 --> 00:16:07.914
ALAN SEALES: Yes,
Silas is 2 and 1/2.

00:16:07.914 --> 00:16:10.330
JESSICA BIEL: Almost 2 and
1/2, yeah, two and some change.

00:16:10.330 --> 00:16:12.820
ALAN SEALES: That's a
great age, isn't it?

00:16:12.820 --> 00:16:14.360
JESSICA BIEL: It
is and it isn't.

00:16:14.360 --> 00:16:17.240
It can be really great and
then it can be really terrible.

00:16:17.240 --> 00:16:19.031
ALAN SEALES: I've got
a 2 and 1/2 year old.

00:16:19.031 --> 00:16:20.490
I feel you.

00:16:20.490 --> 00:16:23.720
Has being a mother in
real life influenced

00:16:23.720 --> 00:16:25.960
how you've approached
the character of Cora

00:16:25.960 --> 00:16:27.860
here in the center?

00:16:27.860 --> 00:16:30.700
JESSICA BIEL: I think
just inherently yes, it

00:16:30.700 --> 00:16:37.120
has to, because now I have an
actual understanding of what

00:16:37.120 --> 00:16:40.980
that relationship is.

00:16:40.980 --> 00:16:43.320
If I didn't have a
kid, yeah, of course

00:16:43.320 --> 00:16:49.950
you can evoke as many
feelings as you can possibly

00:16:49.950 --> 00:16:52.190
build up in your
body to understand

00:16:52.190 --> 00:16:53.400
what that feels like.

00:16:53.400 --> 00:16:57.110
But it will never compare
to the actual feeling of it

00:16:57.110 --> 00:17:00.870
and the actual doing of it,
being a parent every day.

00:17:00.870 --> 00:17:06.410
And it's like the
best research ever,

00:17:06.410 --> 00:17:08.270
just having to
exist with your kid

00:17:08.270 --> 00:17:11.920
everyday to understand what
it would be like, you know,

00:17:11.920 --> 00:17:15.819
like if a person does this
kind of a thing that she does.

00:17:15.819 --> 00:17:18.569
The trickle effect for
her life, specifically

00:17:18.569 --> 00:17:21.470
like what happens to her
and her family and her kid

00:17:21.470 --> 00:17:25.660
and her relationship-- does
she ever see him again?

00:17:25.660 --> 00:17:28.689
These are big
questions when somebody

00:17:28.689 --> 00:17:29.730
does something like this.

00:17:29.730 --> 00:17:34.660
So I have a lot of emotions
that come up for me

00:17:34.660 --> 00:17:37.660
when we shoot stuff
and when we deal

00:17:37.660 --> 00:17:41.760
with the mom-child
relationship, because if I

00:17:41.760 --> 00:17:44.660
couldn't see my kid again,
I would not make it.

00:17:44.660 --> 00:17:47.080
I would just die on
the floor right here.

00:17:47.080 --> 00:17:48.280
ALAN SEALES: Right.

00:17:48.280 --> 00:17:50.210
Yeah, I hear you.

00:17:50.210 --> 00:17:51.774
Question over here?

00:17:51.774 --> 00:17:52.690
AUDIENCE: Hi, Jessica.

00:17:52.690 --> 00:17:53.889
JESSICA BIEL: Hi.

00:17:53.889 --> 00:17:54.930
AUDIENCE: It looks great.

00:17:54.930 --> 00:17:55.360
Congratulations.

00:17:55.360 --> 00:17:55.790
JESSICA BIEL: Thank you.

00:17:55.790 --> 00:17:56.690
AUDIENCE: It looks
really awesome.

00:17:56.690 --> 00:17:58.320
Really excited to watch it.

00:17:58.320 --> 00:18:00.900
So you're here,
house of YouTube.

00:18:00.900 --> 00:18:03.270
And obviously there's
a lot of places

00:18:03.270 --> 00:18:06.170
where people can get kind
of amazing premium content

00:18:06.170 --> 00:18:07.930
like this.

00:18:07.930 --> 00:18:10.750
How do you, either as an
actress or executive producer--

00:18:10.750 --> 00:18:12.500
you've been in the
business a long time--

00:18:12.500 --> 00:18:16.350
how do you see marketing
different nowadays

00:18:16.350 --> 00:18:19.370
than it's been in the
past, because people

00:18:19.370 --> 00:18:20.900
have so many options?

00:18:20.900 --> 00:18:24.430
Love your thoughts either as an
actress or executive producer.

00:18:24.430 --> 00:18:26.950
JESSICA BIEL: I mean you're
right, it's changed so much.

00:18:26.950 --> 00:18:30.070
I think when I was
younger and we really

00:18:30.070 --> 00:18:35.280
didn't have this kind of access
or these kind of platforms,

00:18:35.280 --> 00:18:38.960
everything was dependent on
the studio or the network,

00:18:38.960 --> 00:18:41.270
and you did everything,
and you didn't do anything.

00:18:41.270 --> 00:18:44.740
As one of the creative
people, you just kind of did

00:18:44.740 --> 00:18:47.810
what they told you to do and
you would go do an interview

00:18:47.810 --> 00:18:50.340
or you would do a magazine
cover and that was kind of it.

00:18:50.340 --> 00:18:52.280
It was very simple.

00:18:52.280 --> 00:18:55.650
And now I feel so
much more involved.

00:18:55.650 --> 00:18:57.490
I'm talking to USA all the time.

00:18:57.490 --> 00:19:01.400
We're collaborating on,
what am I going to post?

00:19:01.400 --> 00:19:03.590
What are you guys posting?

00:19:03.590 --> 00:19:09.500
How can we push the marketing
campaign with my personal help,

00:19:09.500 --> 00:19:12.040
with my personal platforms,
with their platforms?

00:19:15.040 --> 00:19:18.280
It's very much more of
like a community thing.

00:19:18.280 --> 00:19:20.300
And it's really nice
because you feel

00:19:20.300 --> 00:19:23.880
like you have a hand in
helping to get out there.

00:19:23.880 --> 00:19:27.310
And I guess that means you also
have a hand in if it fails,

00:19:27.310 --> 00:19:29.400
that nobody cared and
all the stuff you did,

00:19:29.400 --> 00:19:30.320
it didn't matter.

00:19:30.320 --> 00:19:32.600
But at least you're part of it.

00:19:32.600 --> 00:19:35.390
I feel much more a part of
it from the creative side.

00:19:35.390 --> 00:19:39.610
And I guess from the
producorial standpoint,

00:19:39.610 --> 00:19:42.286
as much help as you can
get to get the word out

00:19:42.286 --> 00:19:44.160
for people to be talking
about your material,

00:19:44.160 --> 00:19:47.200
talking about your
show is only helpful.

00:19:47.200 --> 00:19:50.490
So it's been
nothing but positive

00:19:50.490 --> 00:19:53.305
I think when it comes to
marketing, in my experience.

00:19:53.305 --> 00:19:54.430
AUDIENCE: Great, thank you.

00:19:54.430 --> 00:19:55.638
JESSICA BIEL: Yeah, pleasure.

00:19:55.638 --> 00:19:56.987
ALAN SEALES: Yeah?

00:19:56.987 --> 00:19:57.820
AUDIENCE: Hi, there.

00:19:57.820 --> 00:19:58.528
JESSICA BIEL: Hi.

00:19:58.528 --> 00:20:01.330
AUDIENCE: This is something
I've always wondered about.

00:20:01.330 --> 00:20:03.200
When you're reading
something at home

00:20:03.200 --> 00:20:05.390
and you're just to yourself,
I really like this,

00:20:05.390 --> 00:20:06.960
I'm going to make
this into a movie,

00:20:06.960 --> 00:20:09.971
what exactly is the process that
you get in a source material

00:20:09.971 --> 00:20:11.720
when it does come from
a book or something

00:20:11.720 --> 00:20:15.457
like that to be turned into
a television show or a movie?

00:20:15.457 --> 00:20:17.540
How did that work with
this book and how does that

00:20:17.540 --> 00:20:18.206
work in general?

00:20:18.206 --> 00:20:20.370
JESSICA BIEL: Sure.

00:20:20.370 --> 00:20:22.270
Bless you.

00:20:22.270 --> 00:20:26.390
For this book I just
started reading.

00:20:26.390 --> 00:20:30.730
And a couple chapters
in, I just was

00:20:30.730 --> 00:20:34.600
really interested and really
intrigued and then continued on

00:20:34.600 --> 00:20:36.880
and kept calling my partner
Michelle and saying,

00:20:36.880 --> 00:20:39.317
have you made it to
chapter whatever yet?

00:20:39.317 --> 00:20:40.150
You gotta get there.

00:20:40.150 --> 00:20:41.130
It's really good.

00:20:41.130 --> 00:20:43.670
Whoa, this went in a
direction I didn't think

00:20:43.670 --> 00:20:45.650
that it was going to go in.

00:20:45.650 --> 00:20:48.830
And this is a
different experience

00:20:48.830 --> 00:20:52.810
because the material was
already owned by UCP.

00:20:52.810 --> 00:20:55.810
So it wasn't a
situation where I had

00:20:55.810 --> 00:20:58.040
to reach out and try to
get the rights, which we've

00:20:58.040 --> 00:21:00.670
done multiple times before.

00:21:00.670 --> 00:21:04.432
Honestly I will look at a
cover of something and go,

00:21:04.432 --> 00:21:05.390
this looks interesting.

00:21:05.390 --> 00:21:09.060
Somebody call about the
rights, like that fast,

00:21:09.060 --> 00:21:11.660
because the rights
are just gone,

00:21:11.660 --> 00:21:15.210
especially if it has any sort of
notoriety in the literary world

00:21:15.210 --> 00:21:16.370
or anything at all.

00:21:16.370 --> 00:21:18.495
If it's on anybody's list,
if it's on Oprah's list,

00:21:18.495 --> 00:21:20.470
forget it, it's gone.

00:21:20.470 --> 00:21:22.980
Literally I want to
be talking to authors

00:21:22.980 --> 00:21:27.840
who haven't published yet, when
their books are on the way,

00:21:27.840 --> 00:21:30.830
in their third, fourth,
fifth, whatever drafts.

00:21:30.830 --> 00:21:33.264
That's when you want to
be snatching up material.

00:21:33.264 --> 00:21:34.680
So this was a
little bit different

00:21:34.680 --> 00:21:37.260
because UCP was
bringing it to me.

00:21:37.260 --> 00:21:41.630
I had the opportunity to jump on
board right away, which I did.

