00:25:31.542 --> 00:25:32.790
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:25:32.790 --> 00:25:36.040
So you know when you base
something off a book,

00:25:36.040 --> 00:25:39.080
be it a movie or a TV
show, inevitably there

00:25:39.080 --> 00:25:41.850
are going to be some changes.

00:25:41.850 --> 00:25:44.840
Usually the plot gets different
or some things are being cut

00:25:44.840 --> 00:25:46.450
or some things are being added.

00:25:46.450 --> 00:25:48.120
And I guess two questions.

00:25:48.120 --> 00:25:51.310
Firstly, how loosely did
you base it off the book?

00:25:51.310 --> 00:25:54.150
Like is it very
accurate or did you

00:25:54.150 --> 00:25:57.220
get a lot of creative
license with it?

00:25:57.220 --> 00:26:01.250
And secondly, how do you
make those decisions?

00:26:01.250 --> 00:26:05.120
How do you decide what is in
and what is not and what to add?

00:26:05.120 --> 00:26:08.620
JESSICA BIEL: Right,
good questions.

00:26:08.620 --> 00:26:16.100
So we stick pretty closely to
kind of the main real threads

00:26:16.100 --> 00:26:16.790
of this book.

00:26:16.790 --> 00:26:22.740
This book kind of lives in
two worlds, a present time

00:26:22.740 --> 00:26:24.220
and a past.

00:26:24.220 --> 00:26:26.970
And so there's these threads
that we're kind of following.

00:26:26.970 --> 00:26:29.940
And we take some
creative liberties,

00:26:29.940 --> 00:26:32.680
I think, mainly
with the characters.

00:26:32.680 --> 00:26:34.930
I don't even know if you
call them creative liberties.

00:26:34.930 --> 00:26:38.610
We just develop them
in a different way,

00:26:38.610 --> 00:26:40.630
maybe a little bit more
thoroughly in some ways,

00:26:40.630 --> 00:26:42.683
a little bit broader
in other ways,

00:26:42.683 --> 00:26:46.230
took some really acute
ideas of these characters

00:26:46.230 --> 00:26:48.130
and expanded it a little bit.

00:26:48.130 --> 00:26:53.400
But we stick pretty closely
to the main big plot points.

00:26:53.400 --> 00:26:56.650
For example, the Ambrose
character, Bill Pullman's

00:26:56.650 --> 00:27:01.130
character, he's much
different in our show

00:27:01.130 --> 00:27:04.430
than he is in the book.

00:27:04.430 --> 00:27:04.930
Cora--

00:27:04.930 --> 00:27:05.715
ALAN SEALES: Did you
write him that way

00:27:05.715 --> 00:27:08.160
or did Bill choose
to take him that way?

00:27:08.160 --> 00:27:11.390
JESSICA BIEL: We
wrote it that way.

00:27:11.390 --> 00:27:16.240
I think me and my
producers and our creator,

00:27:16.240 --> 00:27:19.100
Derek Simonds, who's
an incredible writer

00:27:19.100 --> 00:27:22.710
and developer, he really saw
that that Ambrose character

00:27:22.710 --> 00:27:28.990
needed more behind it,
needed to really flush out

00:27:28.990 --> 00:27:32.960
this person for television.

00:27:32.960 --> 00:27:39.350
So he took that liberty
and changed that character.

00:27:39.350 --> 00:27:42.730
The second question was--

00:27:42.730 --> 00:27:43.500
can you remind me?

00:27:43.500 --> 00:27:45.874
AUDIENCE: Yeah, how do you go
about making the decisions?

00:27:45.874 --> 00:27:47.730
JESSICA BIEL: Oh,
making the decisions.

00:27:47.730 --> 00:27:52.040
You know, that's a tough
one because you obviously

00:27:52.040 --> 00:27:58.740
want to keep the skeleton
and the real flavor,

00:27:58.740 --> 00:28:03.930
the language of the book,
because you're optioning

00:28:03.930 --> 00:28:06.610
this material for a reason.

00:28:06.610 --> 00:28:09.750
But the formats are
so different, right?

00:28:09.750 --> 00:28:13.520
You can sit and read this book
for days and days and days

00:28:13.520 --> 00:28:16.330
and just slowly get chunks
and be very happy with it,

00:28:16.330 --> 00:28:19.510
whereas what we're trying to
do is keep your attention,

00:28:19.510 --> 00:28:21.990
keep an audience's
interest for--

00:28:21.990 --> 00:28:25.790
I think it's what, 42
minutes with commercials--

00:28:25.790 --> 00:28:27.810
short attend attention spans.

00:28:27.810 --> 00:28:30.740
We have to kind of
drop little nuggets

00:28:30.740 --> 00:28:33.640
along the way to keep you
interested and keep you going.

00:28:33.640 --> 00:28:36.910
So we really have to
cut things and add

00:28:36.910 --> 00:28:40.340
things to keep that in mind,
to keep the suspense moving.

00:28:40.340 --> 00:28:42.340
Whereas you could read
a book and it's just

00:28:42.340 --> 00:28:45.655
like interesting and
romantic and atmospheric,

00:28:45.655 --> 00:28:48.280
but nothing really happens for
a while and you're cool with it.

00:28:48.280 --> 00:28:51.460
That doesn't work
obviously in television.

00:28:51.460 --> 00:28:54.760
But the main person who's
making these decisions

00:28:54.760 --> 00:28:57.050
is Derek, our writer-creator.

00:28:57.050 --> 00:29:00.980
And we are trusting him to
know that this is the best

00:29:00.980 --> 00:29:08.710
way to handle all of these
interweaving storylines, arcs,

00:29:08.710 --> 00:29:12.500
themes, past, present, time.

00:29:12.500 --> 00:29:14.850
It's very complicated what
we've been having to do.

00:29:14.850 --> 00:29:18.510
And how he's been doing has
been quite an amazing feat.

00:29:18.510 --> 00:29:20.840
So hopefully you will agree.

